code_changes.content:
{
  "buggy_files": [
    "fs/nfs/nfs3proc.c",
    "fs/nfs/inode.c"
  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    "nfs3_rpc_wrapper",
    "__nfs_revalidate_inode"
  ],
  "confidence": 0.85,
  "reasoning": "The bug is caused by improper handling of transient RPC errors in the NFS client code. When the NFSv3 RPC layer returns -ERESTARTSYS (error 512) during an EJUKEBOX retry after a signal wakes up the sleep, this transient error is propagated through __nfs_revalidate_inode() without proper distinction from permanent errors like -ESTALE. Specifically: (1) In nfs3proc.c:30-42, nfs3_rpc_wrapper returns -ERESTARTSYS when interrupted during EJUKEBOX retry, which is correct for syscall restart semantics but (2) In inode.c:960-971, __nfs_revalidate_inode treats this transient -ERESTARTSYS error the same as permanent errors - only ESTALE gets special cache-invalidation handling, while all other errors including transient signal-based errors propagate as permanent inode failures. This causes the dentry to be invalidated and leads to autofs mount points being unmounted even on transient RPC failures. The root issue is that transient errors like ERESTARTSYS, ERESTARTNOINTR, or other signal-based RPC interruptions should not result in inode invalidation but should instead be treated as retriable conditions or converted back to the caller before reaching mount validation logic."
}

